WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.740 --> 00:00:03.150
FEMALE SPEAKER: Good afternoon.

00:00:03.150 --> 00:00:05.170
On behalf of Authors
at Google, it

00:00:05.170 --> 00:00:09.000
was my privilege to welcome
philosopher and author Rebecca

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.710
Newberger Goldstein to
Mountain View four years ago.

00:00:12.710 --> 00:00:14.344
She's back.

00:00:14.344 --> 00:00:15.594
I think she enjoyed her visit.

00:00:15.594 --> 00:00:17.930
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:17.930 --> 00:00:21.420
Ms. Goldstein was trained
as a philosopher of science,

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:24.130
receiving her PhD from
Princeton University

00:00:24.130 --> 00:00:26.850
and is the author of
10 prize-winning books

00:00:26.850 --> 00:00:29.440
of both fiction and nonfiction.

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:32.770
She has received fellowships
from the MacArthur Foundation,

00:00:32.770 --> 00:00:35.990
Guggenheim Foundations, the
American Council of Learned

00:00:35.990 --> 00:00:39.570
Societies, and the Radcliffe
Institute, among others.

00:00:39.570 --> 00:00:41.500
Since her last
visit, she has been

00:00:41.500 --> 00:00:47.320
named Humanist of the Year, as
well as Freethought Heroine.

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:49.870
In her latest
book, Ms. Goldstein

00:00:49.870 --> 00:00:54.000
asks us to accept the
one preposterous premise

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.660
that Plato could turn
up in 21st century

00:00:56.660 --> 00:01:00.050
America, an author
on a book tour.

00:01:00.050 --> 00:01:02.030
So here he is at
Google headquarters

00:01:02.030 --> 00:01:04.360
in Mountain View,
California, discussing

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:07.490
with his media escort
and a software engineer

00:01:07.490 --> 00:01:12.620
whether crowdsourcing can
answer all ethical questions?

00:01:12.620 --> 00:01:15.430
So here we are at
Google headquarters

00:01:15.430 --> 00:01:18.290
in Mountain View, California,
where Ms. Goldstein

00:01:18.290 --> 00:01:22.670
will discuss her latest book,
"Plato at the Googleplex."

00:01:22.670 --> 00:01:25.820
Please join me in welcoming
Rebecca Newberger Goldstein.

00:01:25.820 --> 00:01:29.947
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:29.947 --> 00:01:31.280
REBECCA NEWBERGER GOLDSTEIN: Hi.

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:33.100
It's very good to be here.

00:01:33.100 --> 00:01:37.460
Obviously, I was fairly
inspired four years ago when

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:39.995
I visited this place.

00:01:43.530 --> 00:01:48.550
So in bringing Plato back,
I brought him here first

00:01:48.550 --> 00:01:52.050
to Google.

00:01:52.050 --> 00:01:56.400
That solved many
practical problems for me.

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:58.750
I didn't want to have
to waste a lot of time

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:01.240
bringing him up to speed
about everything that's

00:02:01.240 --> 00:02:04.230
happened in the
past 2,400 years.

00:02:04.230 --> 00:02:06.640
So he gets himself
a Chromebook here.

00:02:06.640 --> 00:02:11.630
And he gets addicted very,
very quickly to the internet.

00:02:11.630 --> 00:02:15.920
And by the last
chapter, when he's

00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:18.290
in discussion with
a neuroscientist

00:02:18.290 --> 00:02:23.630
and is about to have
his brain imaged,

00:02:23.630 --> 00:02:27.460
he knows quite a bit of
neuroscience, he's taken a MOOC

00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:31.540
and so he can translate
an ancient argument

00:02:31.540 --> 00:02:35.230
that he put forth in
the "Phaedo," a kind

00:02:35.230 --> 00:02:38.270
of nonreductive
argument that is there

00:02:38.270 --> 00:02:40.720
in the "Phaedo," in
one of his dialogues,

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:44.000
he can translated it into
neuroscientific terms

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:49.270
and it's all thanks to the
first stop here at Google.

00:02:49.270 --> 00:02:53.600
And he was very, very
intrigued by what was going on,

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:56.490
here particularly intrigued by
the whole notion of the cloud,

00:02:56.490 --> 00:02:57.814
as he would be.

00:02:57.814 --> 00:03:02.660
But this an odd book
to say the least.

00:03:02.660 --> 00:03:06.790
It's divided up into two parts.

00:03:06.790 --> 00:03:11.790
There are 10 chapters and
five of them are expository.

00:03:11.790 --> 00:03:17.280
And they go back in time
to the ancient Greeks.

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:19.890
And what was it?

00:03:19.890 --> 00:03:22.890
Well, it's a problem
I and many others

00:03:22.890 --> 00:03:26.440
have tried to solve for
the past two millennia--

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:32.050
I think I solve it-- as to why
the Greeks, the ancient Greeks

00:03:32.050 --> 00:03:34.360
did so much?

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:40.050
They not only discovered
philosophy, but in a sense

00:03:40.050 --> 00:03:46.720
began science, protoscience,
certainly introduced

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:49.510
the study of
abstract mathematics.

00:03:49.510 --> 00:03:53.100
Geometry existed in other
places, certainly in Egypt.

00:03:53.100 --> 00:04:00.190
But the notion of proof, of
axioms, of deduction, this

00:04:00.190 --> 00:04:03.690
really was discovered
by the ancient Greeks.

00:04:03.690 --> 00:04:04.680
What else did they do?

00:04:04.680 --> 00:04:06.140
I mentioned philosophy.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:08.080
Democracy, right?

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:12.650
They discovered democracy, not
quite our form of democracy.

00:04:12.650 --> 00:04:15.790
In fact, the
founders, the writers

00:04:15.790 --> 00:04:19.610
of the American Constitution,
who were all classically

00:04:19.610 --> 00:04:23.690
trained and knew their
Plato, in some sense

00:04:23.690 --> 00:04:29.840
formed our form of
democracy knowing

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:35.100
Plato's criticisms of
Athenian democracy.

00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:36.940
What else do they do?

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:44.050
Well, there's our art,
architecture, timeless poetry,

00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:46.180
tragedies, comedies.

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:51.130
It's still studied
and still move us.

00:04:51.130 --> 00:04:54.770
So this is an
extraordinary people.

00:04:54.770 --> 00:04:57.100
And I'm particularly
interested that they discovered

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:00.970
this kind of peculiar question,
a philosophical question,

00:05:00.970 --> 00:05:05.390
that it is my contention
still exists and is still

00:05:05.390 --> 00:05:08.750
very alive in our society.

00:05:08.750 --> 00:05:13.090
But it's even more
amazing that they

00:05:13.090 --> 00:05:17.430
did what they did because
they did it so quickly.

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:21.030
They went from
anomie and illiteracy

00:05:21.030 --> 00:05:26.000
to Aeschylus and Aristotle
in a matter of 200 years.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:27.940
It had been an
illiterate society.

00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:30.990
There had been literacy
under the Mycenaean culture.

00:05:30.990 --> 00:05:32.770
Then it was destroyed

00:05:32.770 --> 00:05:36.660
They imported the alphabet from
the Phoenicians, adapted it

00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:38.130
to their language.

00:05:38.130 --> 00:05:44.010
And then there's just this
explosion of achievement.

00:05:44.010 --> 00:05:49.050
And what was it that
allowed that to happen?

00:05:49.050 --> 00:05:54.010
I actually have an article
in "The New York Times"

00:05:54.010 --> 00:05:57.290
today under "The
Stone," which is

00:05:57.290 --> 00:06:00.030
where philosophers philosophize.

00:06:00.030 --> 00:06:01.830
And it's a blog.

00:06:01.830 --> 00:06:06.230
And it's about the way in
which our society is so very

00:06:06.230 --> 00:06:10.260
similar to ancient
Greek society.

00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:16.470
And it's very similar in ways
in which Socrates and Plato had

00:06:16.470 --> 00:06:19.580
actually criticized
their society.

00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:24.710
But there are many ways
we're living in a time

00:06:24.710 --> 00:06:31.070
that makes us particularly
able to appreciate the value

00:06:31.070 --> 00:06:34.830
system of the ancient
Greeks and what

00:06:34.830 --> 00:06:36.370
allowed them to achieve so much.

00:06:36.370 --> 00:06:38.695
So that's part of
what I'm doing.

00:06:38.695 --> 00:06:40.070
Because I do think
that there are

00:06:40.070 --> 00:06:45.420
such an interesting parallels
between our extraordinary age

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:48.680
and their extraordinary
age and some

00:06:48.680 --> 00:06:50.820
of the same conditions
in place that

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:55.825
are promoting
explosive discoveries.

00:06:58.670 --> 00:06:59.680
There's that.

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:03.690
But then I actually wanted
to bring Plato forward

00:07:03.690 --> 00:07:10.080
into our time and have
him discourse with us.

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:13.510
Plato-- excuse me--
had used the dialogue

00:07:13.510 --> 00:07:16.790
form and for a very good reason.

00:07:16.790 --> 00:07:19.457
He actually said that
he mistrusted writing.

00:07:19.457 --> 00:07:21.040
He thought that
philosophy is supposed

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:24.500
to be a lived discourse,
a lived conversation.

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:27.490
If you wrote down anything,
there was the danger

00:07:27.490 --> 00:07:28.840
that it would become a doctrine.

00:07:28.840 --> 00:07:29.930
It would become hardened.

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:32.240
You would have disciples.

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:34.675
Thinking would
become thoughtless.

00:07:34.675 --> 00:07:37.640
It would be a matter
of interpreting

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:40.840
what the great man has said.

00:07:40.840 --> 00:07:45.020
And that is the exact opposite
of what you want in philosophy.

00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:49.110
And I think that
that's certainly true.

00:07:49.110 --> 00:07:52.560
So he chose this form,
the dialogue form.

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:55.290
And he used a beloved
figure, Socrates,

00:07:55.290 --> 00:08:01.560
who was already dead at the time
that Plato was writing, perhaps

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:07.910
to bring Socrates forward with
him as he developed philosophy.

00:08:07.910 --> 00:08:11.190
And Plato really did
give us philosophy

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:15.200
as it exists, carved
out the landscape.

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:20.730
It's as if he almost raised up,
like the continent of Atlantis,

00:08:20.730 --> 00:08:24.060
the whole submerged
field of philosophy

00:08:24.060 --> 00:08:26.630
in all its different
subbranches.

00:08:26.630 --> 00:08:28.440
And that's actually
a very good metaphor

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:31.770
to use because our
earliest allusion

00:08:31.770 --> 00:08:36.260
to the myth of Atlantis comes
from Plato in the "Timaeus."

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:39.360
So that actually comes from him.

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:43.320
Anyway, he used Socrates
in these dialogues

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:46.560
and probed his own society.

00:08:46.560 --> 00:08:51.570
And I thought, well, why
not do the same for Plato,

00:08:51.570 --> 00:08:54.280
to bring him forward
into our day,

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:58.530
to put him into a
dialogues with our society?

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:02.820
And as many times as I could,
which turned out to be quite

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:08.020
often, to lift actual
passages from his dialogues

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:14.010
into contemporary dialogues, as
seamlessly as possible so that

00:09:14.010 --> 00:09:16.640
my readers wouldn't know
that this actually came from

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:20.330
a 2,400-year-old man.

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:23.040
And every time I say that,
I think of a Mel Brooks,

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:28.110
Carl Reiner, 2,000-year-old-man
skit that probably most of you

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:29.490
are too young to remember.

00:09:29.490 --> 00:09:31.040
But it's extremely funny.

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:32.820
You should goggle it.

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:40.620
And to seamlessly fit these
passages into our own dialogues

00:09:40.620 --> 00:09:45.120
to show that there's a kind of
relevance still of this man,

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:47.580
in some ways, yes;
in some ways, no.

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:51.360
In many ways we've left
him in the dust, which

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:54.320
I believe he would have wanted.

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:58.440
If, in fact, there is any
philosophical progress made

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:00.700
at all, and I actually
tried to argue

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:04.050
that there is in
this book, then Plato

00:10:04.050 --> 00:10:06.390
can't be completely relevant.

00:10:06.390 --> 00:10:09.590
His answers can't
be completely right.

00:10:09.590 --> 00:10:14.220
Plato himself was committed
to the possibility

00:10:14.220 --> 00:10:16.200
of making
philosophical progress.

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:19.010
That is certainly the most
obvious interpretation

00:10:19.010 --> 00:10:22.730
of the most famous
passage of his writings,

00:10:22.730 --> 00:10:24.550
the myth of the cave.

00:10:24.550 --> 00:10:30.610
You start in darkness,
staring at the shadows

00:10:30.610 --> 00:10:31.920
at the back wall of the cave.

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:35.900
And then you're let
out into reality.

00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:38.510
And he certainly was
committed to making

00:10:38.510 --> 00:10:40.070
philosophical progress.

00:10:40.070 --> 00:10:42.240
If Plato had all
the answers, there

00:10:42.240 --> 00:10:44.340
is no philosophical progress.

00:10:44.340 --> 00:10:46.490
And so Plato couldn't
been right about that.

00:10:46.490 --> 00:10:49.110
Ergo, Plato can't be
right about everything.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:50.440
That's just a syllogism.

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:53.040
It just follows directly.

00:10:53.040 --> 00:10:55.260
So anyway, I bring Plato here.

00:10:55.260 --> 00:11:00.130
He is constantly being
amazed by our society

00:11:00.130 --> 00:11:05.370
and both its good points, what
he judges to be good and bad.

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:07.960
He's certainly amazed by
our science and technology.

00:11:07.960 --> 00:11:11.380
But he's also amazed
at the progress

00:11:11.380 --> 00:11:15.230
we've made philosophically,
ethically, politically.

00:11:15.230 --> 00:11:19.900
And that is part of my
argument, that this process

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:24.420
that he started actually
has had an effect that

00:11:24.420 --> 00:11:27.240
was partly due to
philosophical arguments

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:30.750
that Plato is so surprised
by what he discovers.

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:33.760
So I'm going to start
with the Google ones.

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:38.330
Oh, here are the five places
that I-- five dialogues.

00:11:38.330 --> 00:11:40.300
He first comes here.

00:11:40.300 --> 00:11:43.680
He is in conversation
with his media escort.

00:11:43.680 --> 00:11:46.460
Very-- what is she?

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:49.140
She's a very annoying
woman I have say.

00:11:49.140 --> 00:11:55.210
Very opinionated and she
has no use for philosophy.

00:11:55.210 --> 00:11:56.780
She's a very practical woman.

00:11:56.780 --> 00:12:00.830
And she's actually
able to enlighten

00:12:00.830 --> 00:12:03.590
Plato about certain
things that she

00:12:03.590 --> 00:12:06.000
thinks are intuitively obvious.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:11.180
And that kind of opened his eyes
about certain ethical truths.

00:12:11.180 --> 00:12:15.450
And there's also a software
engineer named Marcus.

00:12:15.450 --> 00:12:19.440
And Marcus believes
that perhaps we

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:27.080
can rig up an ethical answer
search engine, acronym EASE,

00:12:27.080 --> 00:12:31.690
by which we could
algorithmically-- crowdsourcing

00:12:31.690 --> 00:12:35.350
algorithmically answer
ethical questions.

00:12:35.350 --> 00:12:39.070
And Plato quickly
absorbs this idea.

00:12:39.070 --> 00:12:42.000
He's very, very smart.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.840
And he has arguments
against it and from things

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:48.580
that he said a long time ago.

00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:51.290
The next place he
goes, Plato, he now

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:55.170
has his Chromebook cradled
constantly with him,

00:12:55.170 --> 00:12:59.860
is to the 92nd
Street Y. And he's

00:12:59.860 --> 00:13:04.390
on a panel of
child-rearing experts.

00:13:04.390 --> 00:13:10.410
And the topic is how to
raise the exceptional child.

00:13:10.410 --> 00:13:17.020
And his fellow panelist is
a woman named Sophie Zee,

00:13:17.020 --> 00:13:23.530
author of "The Warriors' Guide
to How to produce Off-the-Chart

00:13:23.530 --> 00:13:26.650
Children," a
national best seller,

00:13:26.650 --> 00:13:31.890
and another woman who is
psychoanalytically trained

00:13:31.890 --> 00:13:33.220
in Vienna.

00:13:33.220 --> 00:13:41.590
And her book is-- oh, let me
see if I've-- title of her book?

00:13:41.590 --> 00:13:42.090
OK.

00:13:42.090 --> 00:13:44.910
Well, yes, here's the
invitation actually from the Y.

00:13:44.910 --> 00:13:46.920
"Join us at the Y
for what promises

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:49.010
to be the highlight
of the season.

00:13:49.010 --> 00:13:52.650
Zachary Burns, beloved columnist
for the newspaper of record,

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:56.810
will lead a discussion on "How
to Raise an Exceptional Child.

00:13:56.810 --> 00:14:00.100
With Zach will be best-selling
author, Mitzi Munitz,

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:02.580
author of the
"Esteeming Your Child,

00:14:02.580 --> 00:14:06.620
How Even the Best-Intentioned
Parents Violate, Mutilate,

00:14:06.620 --> 00:14:10.700
and Desecrate Their Children";
Sophie Zee, best-selling author

00:14:10.700 --> 00:14:14.550
of "The Warrior Mother's Guide
to Producing Off-the-Chart

00:14:14.550 --> 00:14:17.150
Children"; and
Plato, best selling

00:14:17.150 --> 00:14:19.980
author of the "Republic."

00:14:19.980 --> 00:14:26.320
And they fight it out there on
the stage of the 92nd Street

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:26.840
Y."

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:34.270
The next thing I do with Plato
is I have him giving advice.

00:14:34.270 --> 00:14:37.570
He's an expert
consultant to an advice

00:14:37.570 --> 00:14:40.150
columnist about love and sex.

00:14:40.150 --> 00:14:43.990
And Plato has an awful lot
to say about love and sex.

00:14:43.990 --> 00:14:47.690
He devoted two
magnificent dialogues

00:14:47.690 --> 00:14:49.630
actually to the subject.

00:14:49.630 --> 00:14:50.930
One is "The Symposium."

00:14:50.930 --> 00:14:53.910
And that's the one from
which we derive our slightly

00:14:53.910 --> 00:14:56.540
degraded idea of Platonic love.

00:14:56.540 --> 00:14:59.030
And that's from
Socrates' speech there

00:14:59.030 --> 00:15:02.270
about how the erotic
longing we direct

00:15:02.270 --> 00:15:06.740
to beautiful young things,
which is our love of beauty,

00:15:06.740 --> 00:15:09.680
ought to be
redirected, sublimated,

00:15:09.680 --> 00:15:14.230
so that all that love
of beauty is directed

00:15:14.230 --> 00:15:18.150
towards beautiful mathematics,
and beautiful laws of nature,

00:15:18.150 --> 00:15:20.760
and beautiful laws of
justice, and eventually

00:15:20.760 --> 00:15:24.560
to the idea of beauty itself.

00:15:24.560 --> 00:15:28.930
So there, he's kind of down
on personal, romantic love.

00:15:28.930 --> 00:15:31.860
He's trying to argue
us out of that.

00:15:31.860 --> 00:15:36.765
And in the "Phaedrus," which
is a dialogue I like even more,

00:15:36.765 --> 00:15:39.800
Plato shows himself
to be really torn

00:15:39.800 --> 00:15:43.150
about this subject
of romantic love.

00:15:43.150 --> 00:15:46.850
He has Socrates, who is
for the first time in any

00:15:46.850 --> 00:15:49.070
of the dialogues,
outside the city walls.

00:15:49.070 --> 00:15:51.720
He's walking in this
lush countryside,

00:15:51.720 --> 00:15:55.290
and he lies down beside a
beautiful boy, Phaedrus,

00:15:55.290 --> 00:15:59.160
beside a sparkling stream,
and they talk of love.

00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:04.140
And Socrates' first
speech to Phaedrus

00:16:04.140 --> 00:16:07.610
argues against the madness
of love, to be taken over,

00:16:07.610 --> 00:16:10.200
to be possessed
by another person,

00:16:10.200 --> 00:16:15.970
and to direct all of your erotic
energy towards him or her.

00:16:15.970 --> 00:16:18.690
And then, Socrates, as
they're about to leave,

00:16:18.690 --> 00:16:21.090
they're about to
step over the stream,

00:16:21.090 --> 00:16:22.810
and he says, wait a minute.

00:16:22.810 --> 00:16:24.690
I am ashamed.

00:16:24.690 --> 00:16:27.870
I had offended the god Eros.

00:16:27.870 --> 00:16:34.650
And he gives another speech,
completely reversing himself,

00:16:34.650 --> 00:16:38.130
on the glories of
the madness of love.

00:16:38.130 --> 00:16:41.175
He's in a very strange mood,
Plato, when he writes this.

00:16:41.175 --> 00:16:44.130
This is really out of
character for Plato.

00:16:44.130 --> 00:16:48.910
So much so that many
of us, including me,

00:16:48.910 --> 00:16:49.880
believe he was in love.

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:51.300
He was in love
when he wrote that.

00:16:51.300 --> 00:16:55.250
And we even think there's
etymological evidence

00:16:55.250 --> 00:16:58.140
within the ancient Greek
pointing to whom he

00:16:58.140 --> 00:17:01.090
was in love with, which
would actually makes sense,

00:17:01.090 --> 00:17:03.370
the character that
we've arrived at.

00:17:03.370 --> 00:17:07.310
But this is actually one
of the reasons I love Plato

00:17:07.310 --> 00:17:10.710
because he philosophizes
with his whole soul.

00:17:10.710 --> 00:17:13.510
If, in fact, he's
fallen in love and he

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:15.460
thinks this is a
good thing, he's

00:17:15.460 --> 00:17:18.770
going to philosophically
reverse his ideas about it.

00:17:18.770 --> 00:17:22.579
Philosophy for Plato is not
just a mind-- it's not a game.

00:17:22.579 --> 00:17:24.021
It's not an intellectual game.

00:17:24.021 --> 00:17:26.020
It's not a way of showing
off how smart you are,

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:29.460
which often happens
in the Academy.

00:17:29.460 --> 00:17:32.820
Of course, he founded of the
Academy, the first Academy.

00:17:32.820 --> 00:17:38.180
He founded the prototype
of the European university.

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:41.660
But for Plato, it
is all about trying

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:43.300
to figure out how to live.

00:17:43.300 --> 00:17:46.110
And so we would reverse
himself if he was in love.

00:17:46.110 --> 00:17:48.090
He would rethink his ideas.

00:17:48.090 --> 00:17:51.320
In fact, Plato was constantly
rethinking his ideas.

00:17:51.320 --> 00:17:53.730
When we teach Plato,
we say this is

00:17:53.730 --> 00:17:56.010
what Plato said,
theory of forms,

00:17:56.010 --> 00:18:00.560
division between the mind
and the soul and the body.

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:01.900
That's quite wrong.

00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:04.470
Plato himself
subjects those views

00:18:04.470 --> 00:18:08.440
to stringent,
rigorous criticism.

00:18:08.440 --> 00:18:10.840
So much so, that
in later dialogues

00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:12.350
he actually gets them up.

00:18:12.350 --> 00:18:16.100
So anyway, he has a lot
to say about love and sex.

