But he was also eager to get
an insider's look at Google.

00:30:42.050 --> 00:30:45.690
The whole cloud idea had caught
his fancy for some reason.

00:30:45.690 --> 00:30:48.390
Before I had wanted him to
skip the tour since I thought

00:30:48.390 --> 00:30:50.720
it would be exhausting for him.

00:30:50.720 --> 00:30:52.150
But then the kind
of conversation

00:30:52.150 --> 00:30:54.770
he was intent on having was
every bit as exhausting,

00:30:54.770 --> 00:30:55.919
at least for me.

00:30:55.919 --> 00:30:57.710
He asked me if it would
be possible to take

00:30:57.710 --> 00:31:00.710
the tour after he gave his
Authors at Google Talk?

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:01.716
No, I told him.

00:31:01.716 --> 00:31:03.340
That's out of the
question since that's

00:31:03.340 --> 00:31:06.060
when you're signing the books.

00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:08.440
He was all for skipping
the book signing.

00:31:08.440 --> 00:31:11.480
But obviously, that wasn't
going to happen on my watch.

00:31:11.480 --> 00:31:13.010
When it comes to
that sort of thing,

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:15.820
then I'm the one who has
to be the tyrant since I

00:31:15.820 --> 00:31:17.180
answer to the publishers.

00:31:17.180 --> 00:31:20.850
And believe me, they keep
track of how their authors do

00:31:20.850 --> 00:31:23.620
with the various media
escorts, comparing our sales

00:31:23.620 --> 00:31:25.470
records with one another.

00:31:25.470 --> 00:31:28.140
Marcus tipped the
balance by telling Plato,

00:31:28.140 --> 00:31:31.270
again, that not only did he
want to challenge his view,

00:31:31.270 --> 00:31:33.100
but he could also
explain the way

00:31:33.100 --> 00:31:35.610
that Google works, the
way the search engine is

00:31:35.610 --> 00:31:37.990
able to deliver the right
information to people

00:31:37.990 --> 00:31:40.660
with such accuracy.

00:31:40.660 --> 00:31:44.970
You're not going to get that
on the tour of the Googleplex

00:31:44.970 --> 00:31:46.630
he told Plato, since
the answers you're

00:31:46.630 --> 00:31:50.260
looking for lie in the sphere of
abstraction, which of course is

00:31:50.260 --> 00:31:51.950
right up your alley.

00:31:51.950 --> 00:31:54.450
With that, Plato was so
happy that he actually

00:31:54.450 --> 00:31:57.370
allowed himself a real smile,
not just the hint of one.

00:31:57.370 --> 00:32:00.430
And I sent the tour guides, who
seemed genuinely disappointed,

00:32:00.430 --> 00:32:01.490
on their way.

00:32:01.490 --> 00:32:04.460
Apparently, they were
big fans of Plato's too.

00:32:04.460 --> 00:32:06.390
Go figure.

00:32:06.390 --> 00:32:08.120
Plato got right
down to business,

00:32:08.120 --> 00:32:12.111
asking Marcus what were the
points he wanted to challenge?

00:32:12.111 --> 00:32:12.610
OK.

00:32:12.610 --> 00:32:14.810
Let me just reiterate
the major points that

00:32:14.810 --> 00:32:18.110
have emerged so far, at least
as I see them, Marcus said.

00:32:18.110 --> 00:32:20.050
You assume that if
there's knowledge,

00:32:20.050 --> 00:32:22.500
especially if it's a
nontrivial knowledge that's

00:32:22.500 --> 00:32:24.950
difficult to come by, then
those who have the knowledge

00:32:24.950 --> 00:32:27.380
are the few, the experts
in that knowledge.

00:32:27.380 --> 00:32:28.600
Is that right?

00:32:28.600 --> 00:32:29.470
Yes, Plato said.

00:32:29.470 --> 00:32:34.600
That this is so seems to
me almost a tautology.

00:32:34.600 --> 00:32:36.261
We shall see, said Marcus.

00:32:36.261 --> 00:32:36.760
OK.

00:32:36.760 --> 00:32:39.630
Then you also assume that
there is such a thing

00:32:39.630 --> 00:32:41.890
as knowledge about how we
ought to live our lives,

00:32:41.890 --> 00:32:44.260
that it's not just a matter
of personal preference

00:32:44.260 --> 00:32:46.060
or cultural norms, say.

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:48.970
And that this knowledge is
nontrivial and hard to come by.

00:32:48.970 --> 00:32:50.520
Am I right?

00:32:50.520 --> 00:32:51.480
Yes, Plato said.

00:32:51.480 --> 00:32:54.880
It must certainly be nontrivial
since so many people get

00:32:54.880 --> 00:32:58.490
it wrong, living lives that
are almost at a Charlie Sheen

00:32:58.490 --> 00:33:00.620
level of ask dumbness.

00:33:00.620 --> 00:33:02.460
He didn't, I said to Cheryl.

00:33:02.460 --> 00:33:05.290
He did, repeated
me word for word.

00:33:05.290 --> 00:33:09.010
Even Marcus had to all-out
laugh, instead of snicker.

00:33:09.010 --> 00:33:10.440
OK, then Marcus went on.

00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:12.690
So then the implication
of these two assumptions

00:33:12.690 --> 00:33:14.590
is that if anybody
has this knowledge,

00:33:14.590 --> 00:33:17.640
and I suppose it's consistent
with your two assumptions,

00:33:17.640 --> 00:33:18.980
that nobody has it.

00:33:18.980 --> 00:33:21.400
But if, in fact, anyone
has this knowledge,

00:33:21.400 --> 00:33:22.990
it can only belong
to those who have

00:33:22.990 --> 00:33:25.230
managed to think
their way to it.

00:33:25.230 --> 00:33:26.290
Am I right?

00:33:26.290 --> 00:33:27.890
Yes, said Plato.

00:33:27.890 --> 00:33:29.730
So according to
you, this knowledge

00:33:29.730 --> 00:33:32.060
is something like
mathematical knowledge.

00:33:32.060 --> 00:33:35.010
It's just as objective,
its truth not determined

00:33:35.010 --> 00:33:37.890
by personal preferences
or societal norms.

00:33:37.890 --> 00:33:41.050
And it's just as non-trivial
and difficult to access,

00:33:41.050 --> 00:33:43.070
being a matter of reasoning.

00:33:43.070 --> 00:33:44.600
Yes, said Plato.

00:33:44.600 --> 00:33:46.070
I agreed to all of this.

00:33:46.070 --> 00:33:47.700
In fact, I would go
further and claim

00:33:47.700 --> 00:33:50.630
that it is not only like
mathematical reasoning,

00:33:50.630 --> 00:33:53.790
but that mathematics itself
goes into the knowledge.

00:33:53.790 --> 00:33:54.800
OK, Marcus said.

00:33:54.800 --> 00:33:57.280
But let's just stick with
the weaker proposition

00:33:57.280 --> 00:33:59.990
for the purposes
of my refuting you.

00:33:59.990 --> 00:34:01.330
Yes, agreed Plato.

00:34:01.330 --> 00:34:03.610
That makes dialectical sense.

00:34:03.610 --> 00:34:04.800
OK, Marcus said.

00:34:04.800 --> 00:34:06.750
And then took several
moments to breathe.

00:34:06.750 --> 00:34:10.300
He was, as my mother used
to put it, overexcited.

00:34:10.300 --> 00:34:13.469
OK, he said again, what
all of this implies,

00:34:13.469 --> 00:34:15.690
as Cheryl was
quick to point out,

00:34:15.690 --> 00:34:18.480
is that only those who
are gifted in reasoning

00:34:18.480 --> 00:34:20.810
can discover how
we ought to live.

00:34:20.810 --> 00:34:23.650
There's no other way
to access these truths,

00:34:23.650 --> 00:34:26.960
meaning that nonphilosophical
people who can't follow

00:34:26.960 --> 00:34:28.980
philosophical arguments,
have to accept

00:34:28.980 --> 00:34:31.530
the conclusions from
the philosophers?

00:34:31.530 --> 00:34:33.330
Yes, said Plato.

00:34:33.330 --> 00:34:35.920
Hence the enormous
obligations to others

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:37.770
the philosophers have.

00:34:37.770 --> 00:34:42.150
Including, said
Marcus, obligations

00:34:42.150 --> 00:34:44.639
to tell others how
they should be living,

00:34:44.639 --> 00:34:47.420
to legislate morals for them?

00:34:47.420 --> 00:34:50.130
No, said Plato, not
in every respect.

00:34:50.130 --> 00:34:53.070
No, since as was also
pointed out by Cheryl,

00:34:53.070 --> 00:34:55.159
there are many matters
that lie entirely

00:34:55.159 --> 00:34:58.280
in the sphere of personal
or cultural preferences.

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:01.410
And many such decisions,
which are there for entirely

00:35:01.410 --> 00:35:04.850
a matter for an individual to
decide for himself or herself."

00:35:04.850 --> 00:35:07.360
He's already been corrected
about his sexist language.

00:35:07.360 --> 00:35:08.690
So he overcorrects.

00:35:08.690 --> 00:35:10.560
And it's all himself or herself.

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:13.200
Cheryl corrected him on this.

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:16.270
"So for an individual to
decide for himself, or herself,

00:35:16.270 --> 00:35:18.750
or to let society
decide for him or her

00:35:18.750 --> 00:35:21.170
will help to make for
a life worth living.

00:35:21.170 --> 00:35:23.590
So that, for example,
if I am of such a nature

00:35:23.590 --> 00:35:26.240
that I need to test my
manhood-- I hope it's not

00:35:26.240 --> 00:35:28.620
sexist to mention
manhood in this context,

00:35:28.620 --> 00:35:30.820
he asked, looking at me?

00:35:30.820 --> 00:35:34.940
Cheryl said, why don't you
just say test your courage?

00:35:34.940 --> 00:35:36.752
Women test their courage too.

00:35:36.752 --> 00:35:37.960
Yes, you're right, he agreed.

00:35:37.960 --> 00:35:40.510
If I say I am of
such a nature that I

00:35:40.510 --> 00:35:43.670
need to test my courage
by taking repeated risks,

00:35:43.670 --> 00:35:46.040
then I am free to do
so insofar as the risks

00:35:46.040 --> 00:35:48.760
I take do not involve
any moral transgressions.

00:35:48.760 --> 00:35:51.350
A great deal of the substance
of a life worth living

00:35:51.350 --> 00:35:53.730
is made up of
decisions of this sort.

00:35:53.730 --> 00:35:56.340
But not all of them,
Marcus prodded?

00:35:56.340 --> 00:35:59.300
No, not all of
them, Plato agree.

00:35:59.300 --> 00:36:03.010
And these are the contributions
to a life worth living

00:36:03.010 --> 00:36:06.260
that a philosophically
unintelligent person can't

00:36:06.260 --> 00:36:10.840
decide for themselves, but must
instead turn the decision over

00:36:10.840 --> 00:36:13.840
to the philosophically
intelligent, Marcus said.

00:36:13.840 --> 00:36:15.550
Not quite, said Plato.

00:36:15.550 --> 00:36:18.270
Nobody, the
philosophically intelligent

00:36:18.270 --> 00:36:20.930
any more than the
philosophically nonintelligent,

00:36:20.930 --> 00:36:24.210
can decide these matters
for himself or herself

00:36:24.210 --> 00:36:26.950
since there are objective
facts of the matter.

00:36:26.950 --> 00:36:28.950
Those who can access
such knowledge

00:36:28.950 --> 00:36:31.160
are no more able to
change the facts of how

00:36:31.160 --> 00:36:33.690
we are to live
than anybody else.

00:36:33.690 --> 00:36:36.350
Like everybody else,
they must abide by them.

00:36:36.350 --> 00:36:38.010
The one difference
is that they are

00:36:38.010 --> 00:36:40.660
able to discover, through the
special talents and training

00:36:40.660 --> 00:36:43.230
that are theirs,
what the facts are.

00:36:43.230 --> 00:36:46.340
So they are not imposing
their personal will on others,

00:36:46.340 --> 00:36:49.660
any more than mathematicians are
imposing their wills on others

00:36:49.660 --> 00:36:51.650
by informing
nonmathematicians what

00:36:51.650 --> 00:36:53.550
the mathematical truths are.

00:36:53.550 --> 00:36:56.430
They are simply sharing
their knowledge with others,

00:36:56.430 --> 00:36:59.550
knowledge that others cannot
access for themselves,

00:36:59.550 --> 00:37:01.740
lacking the requisite
cognitive skills,

00:37:01.740 --> 00:37:04.190
a matter of both of
talent and training.

00:37:04.190 --> 00:37:06.910
This seems to me no
more unfair than that

00:37:06.910 --> 00:37:09.180
the mathematically
intelligent share

00:37:09.180 --> 00:37:10.780
their knowledge of
mathematics with

00:37:10.780 --> 00:37:12.900
the mathematically
unintelligent.

00:37:12.900 --> 00:37:15.610
So, for example, you
as a software engineer,

00:37:15.610 --> 00:37:18.210
possess considerable
mathematical intelligence

00:37:18.210 --> 00:37:19.450
I would assume?

00:37:19.450 --> 00:37:22.170
Yes, Marcus said, I
suppose you could say that.

00:37:22.170 --> 00:37:24.510
And by working here
at Google, Plato said,

00:37:24.510 --> 00:37:26.140
you are able to
provide the benefits

00:37:26.140 --> 00:37:27.637
of your mathematical
intelligence

00:37:27.637 --> 00:37:29.970
to others who are lacking
this kind of intelligence, who

00:37:29.970 --> 00:37:32.850
make use of your
powerful search engine

00:37:32.850 --> 00:37:36.250
while simply regarding
it as techno-magic.

00:37:36.250 --> 00:37:38.840
The difference, Marco
said, is that not everybody

00:37:38.840 --> 00:37:42.610
believes himself to be good
in math or even cares too be.

00:37:42.610 --> 00:37:44.900
In fact, only those who
are in fact good in math

00:37:44.900 --> 00:37:47.280
give a hoot about whether
they're good at it or not.

00:37:47.280 --> 00:37:50.790
But everybody cares about
living his life well

00:37:50.790 --> 00:37:53.400
and has strong views
about how best to do it.

00:37:53.400 --> 00:37:55.110
And if you tell
him that he's just

00:37:55.110 --> 00:37:58.750
lacking the cognitive ability to
figure it all out for himself,

00:37:58.750 --> 00:38:04.850
he's going to have some
harsh words for you."

00:38:04.850 --> 00:38:08.680
I'm going to stop here
because one thing I think

00:38:08.680 --> 00:38:13.640
Plato got very right is
that discourse, dialogue

00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:19.720
conversation, give and
take, Q&amp;A, is essential.

00:38:19.720 --> 00:38:23.130
So I am going to stop here.

00:38:23.130 --> 00:38:31.090
Maybe you can anticipate
what Marcus's objection

00:38:31.090 --> 00:38:33.500
to what Plato just
said would be?

00:38:33.500 --> 00:38:36.150
Maybe you can even
anticipate what

00:38:36.150 --> 00:38:39.550
Plato would say in
answer to Marcus?

00:38:39.550 --> 00:38:41.840
Marcus basically is
trying to take down

00:38:41.840 --> 00:38:47.200
the idea of ethical experts,
philosophical experts.

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:54.260
So, yeah, I'm going to stop
here and ask for your questions.

00:38:54.260 --> 00:38:55.562
Thank you.

00:38:55.562 --> 00:39:00.330
[APPLAUSE]

00:39:00.330 --> 00:39:02.410
AUDIENCE: My only
question is am I

00:39:02.410 --> 00:39:07.160
expected to have read Plato
before I can enjoy this book?

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:09.580
REBECCA NEWBERGER GOLDSTEIN:
I do quote from him

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:12.020
or reference him.

00:39:12.020 --> 00:39:15.970
And it's surprising how
often what he has to say

00:39:15.970 --> 00:39:19.150
is actually relevant
to conversations

00:39:19.150 --> 00:39:22.860
that we are having, that are
very current in our society.

00:39:22.860 --> 00:39:23.890
But no, of course not.

00:39:23.890 --> 00:39:24.950
You don't have to.

00:39:24.950 --> 00:39:28.500
Although I am getting emails
from people saying that they've

00:39:28.500 --> 00:39:30.560
opened up their
Plato books, that

00:39:30.560 --> 00:39:36.260
haven't been opened since
they were freshman in college.

00:39:36.260 --> 00:39:39.210
I'll tell you something.

00:39:39.210 --> 00:39:46.940
And I think so much of Plato
is really terrifically boring.

00:39:46.940 --> 00:39:51.360
And he's raising these
questions for the first time.

00:39:51.360 --> 00:39:52.800
And that's magnificent.

00:39:52.800 --> 00:39:54.060
That's amazing.

00:39:54.060 --> 00:39:57.840
And philosophy is divided into
all these subspecialities.

00:39:57.840 --> 00:40:03.460
For just about any area of
human inquiry or concern,

00:40:03.460 --> 00:40:06.164
there's a corresponding
area of philosophy.

00:40:06.164 --> 00:40:07.705
So philosophy of
language; philosophy

00:40:07.705 --> 00:40:10.092
of science, which is my
own particular interest;

00:40:10.092 --> 00:40:11.550
philosophy of
mathematics, I'm also

00:40:11.550 --> 00:40:14.870
quite interested in that;
philosophy of history;

00:40:14.870 --> 00:40:17.860
philosophy of religion;
philosophy of art;

00:40:17.860 --> 00:40:22.389
ethics; political philosophy;
philosophy of knowledge itself,

00:40:22.389 --> 00:40:22.930
epistemology.

00:40:26.180 --> 00:40:27.970
I'm leaving things out.

00:40:27.970 --> 00:40:31.400
And now, applied
ethics as well So

00:40:31.400 --> 00:40:36.830
applied ethics is applied to the
environment, to medical ethics,

00:40:36.830 --> 00:40:41.860
to minority concerns.

00:40:41.860 --> 00:40:46.770
So for every area, there's
a corresponding area

00:40:46.770 --> 00:40:47.880
of philosophy.

00:40:47.880 --> 00:40:52.760
What's amazing is Plato actually
carved out that entire terrain.

00:40:52.760 --> 00:40:56.080
He really asked the
paradigmatic questions

00:40:56.080 --> 00:40:58.850
in philosophy of mathematics,
in philosophy of language,

00:40:58.850 --> 00:41:04.030
in philosophy of
religion, epistemology.

00:41:04.030 --> 00:41:05.440
Certainly ethics,
but that he had

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:08.180
gotten from Socrates,
that concern with ethics

00:41:08.180 --> 00:41:11.860
and, well, perhaps to some
extent, political philosophy

00:41:11.860 --> 00:41:14.210
he had gotten from Socrates.

00:41:14.210 --> 00:41:16.460
But he asked these questions.

00:41:16.460 --> 00:41:19.660
And what else is so interesting,
philosophical questions

00:41:19.660 --> 00:41:21.660
are very peculiar.

00:41:21.660 --> 00:41:25.860
A lot of the questions that
were first asked by philosophers

00:41:25.860 --> 00:41:28.870
were protoscientific questions.

00:41:28.870 --> 00:41:31.960
As science progressed,
they were taken out

00:41:31.960 --> 00:41:34.400
of the domain of philosophy.

00:41:34.400 --> 00:41:39.420
The empirical methodology caught
up and they were answered.

00:41:39.420 --> 00:41:42.440
So all of physics
and cosmology started

00:41:42.440 --> 00:41:43.850
in the domain of philosophy.

00:41:43.850 --> 00:41:45.900
It was called
natural philosophy.

00:41:45.900 --> 00:41:50.250
And it really pretty much
remained as philosophy

00:41:50.250 --> 00:41:54.120
until the 16th,
17th century, when

00:41:54.120 --> 00:41:58.900
the scientific method really--
this beautiful marriage

00:41:58.900 --> 00:42:03.940
of empiricism and mathematical
description-- that part Plato

00:42:03.940 --> 00:42:06.530
got right-- were
brought together

00:42:06.530 --> 00:42:08.200
and we really started
making headway

00:42:08.200 --> 00:42:12.310
and overturned the
Aristotelian/Ptolemaic system

00:42:12.310 --> 00:42:16.750
that had dominated in
science until the reemergence

00:42:16.750 --> 00:42:19.610
of science, or real
science I would say,

00:42:19.610 --> 00:42:22.430
with Copernicus,
Kepler, Galileo.

00:42:22.430 --> 00:42:25.630
By the way, Kepler
and Galileo, who

00:42:25.630 --> 00:42:31.310
so valued mathematical
description,

00:42:31.310 --> 00:42:34.770
always referred to Plato
as the Divine Plato.

00:42:34.770 --> 00:42:37.890
And if you read the "Timaeus,"
you'll understand why.

00:42:37.890 --> 00:42:41.350
Because that notion
that it's math--

00:42:41.350 --> 00:42:43.690
he's pretty much given
up on the theory of forms

00:42:43.690 --> 00:42:47.350
by the "Timaeus"--
and it's math.

00:42:47.350 --> 00:42:50.680
And it's, in fact, the
most beautiful math.

00:42:50.680 --> 00:42:54.510
So if we have two
theories and they're both

00:42:54.510 --> 00:42:56.900
adequate to explain
what we're observing,

00:42:56.900 --> 00:42:59.510
go with the mathematically
beautiful one

00:42:59.510 --> 00:43:01.330
and you'll go towards the truth.

00:43:01.330 --> 00:43:06.010
Kepler, Copernicus, that's
what they were saying.

00:43:06.010 --> 00:43:09.280
In fact, Kepler-- I'm
sorry, Galileo had said,

00:43:09.280 --> 00:43:11.970
he wouldn't even have
bothered with experimen--

00:43:11.970 --> 00:43:14.550
because the math, the
beautiful math was enough--

00:43:14.550 --> 00:43:17.090
if his critics weren't
so stupid so that he

00:43:17.090 --> 00:43:20.190
had to actually demonstrate
to them with experiments.

00:43:20.190 --> 00:43:25.680
So this kind of notion of the
beautiful math leading the way,

00:43:25.680 --> 00:43:26.540
this is Plato.

00:43:26.540 --> 00:43:31.210
But in any case, a lot
of scientific questions

00:43:31.210 --> 00:43:34.330
first belonged to philosophy.

00:43:34.330 --> 00:43:36.310
And then the
empirical methodology

00:43:36.310 --> 00:43:40.990
catches up; psychology,
same thing; linguistics.

00:43:40.990 --> 00:43:45.410
Logic, which belonged to the
sphere of philosophy, now

00:43:45.410 --> 00:43:48.500
it takes place in
mathematics departments.

00:43:48.500 --> 00:43:52.450
So as science
progresses, it is true

00:43:52.450 --> 00:43:56.350
that the set of philosophical
questions somewhat shrinks.

00:43:56.350 --> 00:44:00.140
But I actually think that
there's a conservation because

00:44:00.140 --> 00:44:02.940
of philosophical
questions because science

00:44:02.940 --> 00:44:07.240
itself presents so many
philosophical questions to us,

00:44:07.240 --> 00:44:09.670
trying to make sense
of the science.

00:44:09.670 --> 00:44:13.060
That's why philosophers always
have to keep up with science.

00:44:13.060 --> 00:44:16.080
But why am I saying all
of this in answer to you?

00:44:16.080 --> 00:44:18.880
Because I didn't say it before
and I think it's important.

00:44:18.880 --> 00:44:21.750
But no, you don't know to Plato.

00:44:21.750 --> 00:44:24.610
As much as I can,
I bring him in.

00:44:24.610 --> 00:44:26.110
I know I why I was
saying it to you.

00:44:26.110 --> 00:44:30.530
Because what philosophers
are often-- you know,

00:44:30.530 --> 00:44:32.740
we're often
defending ourselves--

00:44:32.740 --> 00:44:35.420
especially if you're a
philosopher like me who

00:44:35.420 --> 00:44:37.940
hangs out mostly with
scientists-- we're often

00:44:37.940 --> 00:44:40.010
defending ourselves
against the charge

00:44:40.010 --> 00:44:43.960
that, look, the
history of philosophy

00:44:43.960 --> 00:44:46.390
is the history of contraction.

00:44:46.390 --> 00:44:54.270
As science expands,
philosophy shrinks, contracts.

00:44:54.270 --> 00:44:58.000
Here is an equation, the
fate of philosophy equation,

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:04.120
as t goes toward infinity, the
set of philosophical questions

00:45:04.120 --> 00:45:05.770
goes towards the null set.

00:45:05.770 --> 00:45:08.680
I mean that, in fact,
eventually science

00:45:08.680 --> 00:45:10.580
will answer all of
these questions.

00:45:10.580 --> 00:45:13.960
I think that's wrong actually.

00:45:13.960 --> 00:45:17.140
And Plato-- this is the
extraordinary thing--

00:45:17.140 --> 00:45:19.160
Plato, even though
he really lived

00:45:19.160 --> 00:45:24.052
before there was any
real science to speak of,

00:45:24.052 --> 00:45:28.020
had some of the best of
antireductive arguments

00:45:28.020 --> 00:45:34.840
against that sort of reduction
of all philosophical questions

00:45:34.840 --> 00:45:35.915
to scientific ones.

00:45:35.915 --> 00:45:37.690
The other place where
you often hear this

00:45:37.690 --> 00:45:42.160
is not science, that philosophy
has no right to exist,

00:45:42.160 --> 00:45:43.220
but religion.

00:45:43.220 --> 00:45:46.320
And that used to be an argument
you would get much more

00:45:46.320 --> 00:45:48.350
often in the bad old days.

00:45:48.350 --> 00:45:50.190
But you still get it actually.

00:45:50.190 --> 00:45:54.330
And Plato also has, in the
youth of Rome, the best argument

00:45:54.330 --> 00:45:58.110
against those who would reduce
philosophical questions,

00:45:58.110 --> 00:46:00.380
in particular ethical
questions, or why is there

00:46:00.380 --> 00:46:03.990
something rather than nothing,
to religious questions,

00:46:03.990 --> 00:46:06.940
but particularly
moral questions.

00:46:06.940 --> 00:46:12.460
He has an incredible argument,
which is still repeated,

00:46:12.460 --> 00:46:16.490
even into our day by the
so-called "new atheists,"

00:46:16.490 --> 00:46:21.720
as to why religion can
never ground morality.

00:46:21.720 --> 00:46:26.040
So he has these two very
prescient arguments,

00:46:26.040 --> 00:46:29.540
on the one side against
scientific reductionism,

00:46:29.540 --> 00:46:31.530
and on the other
side against sort

00:46:31.530 --> 00:46:33.290
of theological reductionism.

00:46:33.290 --> 00:46:38.820
And that's really all you have
to know about Plato, I think.

00:46:38.820 --> 00:46:41.770
That is the most
interesting thing about him.

00:46:41.770 --> 00:46:44.570
He had such a nose
for this peculiar kind

00:46:44.570 --> 00:46:46.120
of philosophical
question, that not

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:50.890
only did he raise this
submerged continent

00:46:50.890 --> 00:46:54.040
of philosophical questions,
he had the prescience

00:46:54.040 --> 00:46:56.010
to see that some
of these questions

00:46:56.010 --> 00:46:59.660
would never be answered, either
by religion or by science,

00:46:59.660 --> 00:47:02.830
but yet could be answered
through human reason

00:47:02.830 --> 00:47:04.520
or we could make
progress with them

00:47:04.520 --> 00:47:10.180
through human reason,
an ongoing process.

00:47:10.180 --> 00:47:13.520
So I think that's the
most important thing

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:15.350
to know about Plato
and not to have

00:47:15.350 --> 00:47:21.490
to wade through so much that's
not terribly interesting to us

00:47:21.490 --> 00:47:23.002
anymore.

00:47:23.002 --> 00:47:25.210
AUDIENCE: I'm actually
interested in the relationship

00:47:25.210 --> 00:47:28.960
between Plato and what he might
think of modern technology.

00:47:28.960 --> 00:47:31.820
And specifically, for
example, what would

00:47:31.820 --> 00:47:35.150
he think about our
extreme preoccupation

00:47:35.150 --> 00:47:36.850
with Facebook and Google?

00:47:36.850 --> 00:47:39.070
Like would that,
for example, make

00:47:39.070 --> 00:47:42.875
us sink deeper into the cave
or allow us to leave the cave?

00:47:42.875 --> 00:47:44.250
REBECCA NEWBERGER
GOLDSTEIN: Yes.

00:47:44.250 --> 00:47:50.850
Actually, yes, this thing that
I have in the "New York Times,"

00:47:50.850 --> 00:47:53.000
"The Stone," is
exactly about this.

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:58.070
It's exactly about
what would Plato tweet?

00:47:58.070 --> 00:48:00.940
I had never tweeted and
I'm not on Facebook.

00:48:00.940 --> 00:48:02.550
I had never been interested.

00:48:02.550 --> 00:48:05.620
But my daughter, who
is much more savvy

00:48:05.620 --> 00:48:08.600
than I am, suggested
to me, how would you

00:48:08.600 --> 00:48:10.310
like to tweet as Plato?

00:48:10.310 --> 00:48:14.080
And I have been tweeting
as Plato for like the past,

00:48:14.080 --> 00:48:15.740
I don't know, three
weeks or something.

00:48:15.740 --> 00:48:18.330
And the handle is platobooktour.

00:48:18.330 --> 00:48:20.260
So Plato is with us now.

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:25.330
I often have him tweeting about
the events that I've gone on.

00:48:25.330 --> 00:48:27.440
And I was just with
a writer last night.

00:48:27.440 --> 00:48:30.160
And he said to me, oh, did you
lie in bed afterwards thinking,

00:48:30.160 --> 00:48:32.020
oh, this is how I should
have answered the question?

00:48:32.020 --> 00:48:33.530
And I said, well,
of course I do.

00:48:33.530 --> 00:48:36.090
I mean it's always
very hard to give

00:48:36.090 --> 00:48:37.610
an adequate answer outright.

00:48:37.610 --> 00:48:42.830
But now, I could have
Plato saying, regarding

00:48:42.830 --> 00:48:45.840
capital punishment question
at Harvard bookstore,

00:48:45.840 --> 00:48:47.470
Goldstein flubbed it.

00:48:47.470 --> 00:48:48.910
Here's what I say.

00:48:48.910 --> 00:48:52.170
So this is just wonderful
for me because I can actually

00:48:52.170 --> 00:48:55.220
answer them much better,
what Plato would have to say.

00:48:55.220 --> 00:48:59.420
Plato, I think,
would be quite struck

00:48:59.420 --> 00:49:06.590
by the way in which we're trying
to answer the questions of how

00:49:06.590 --> 00:49:10.540
to live a life that
matters and that we're all

00:49:10.540 --> 00:49:11.880
preoccupied with that question.

00:49:11.880 --> 00:49:16.080
For a very long time,
religion answered that for us,

00:49:16.080 --> 00:49:20.050
we mattered in the universe
in a very large way.

00:49:20.050 --> 00:49:22.470
God, we mattered to God.

00:49:22.470 --> 00:49:24.500
God was keeping track
of everything we did.

00:49:24.500 --> 00:49:26.255
I was brought up very religious.

00:49:26.255 --> 00:49:32.630
And I believed as a little
girl that if I took a nibble

00:49:32.630 --> 00:49:35.260
from a Hostess, Twinkie
bar, which do not

00:49:35.260 --> 00:49:38.060
have the right
rabbinical symbol on it,

00:49:38.060 --> 00:49:45.820
that the Lord of the Hosts
would take note and punish me.

00:49:45.820 --> 00:49:50.170
I had to do my repentance,
which was terrifying.

00:49:50.170 --> 00:49:54.110
But it certainly gave one a
sense that you really mattered.

00:49:54.110 --> 00:49:57.780
Every single thing
you did mattered.

00:49:57.780 --> 00:50:01.900
For many of us that
kind of confirmation

00:50:01.900 --> 00:50:05.570
of our mattering coming
from that kind of worldview

00:50:05.570 --> 00:50:07.310
no longer resonates.

00:50:07.310 --> 00:50:10.260
And so this question
that actually

00:50:10.260 --> 00:50:13.870
was there in Plato's
society-- his society

00:50:13.870 --> 00:50:15.630
was premonotheistic.

00:50:15.630 --> 00:50:18.970
We are more and more
postmonotheistic.

00:50:18.970 --> 00:50:22.090
And we're going
towards the same kind

00:50:22.090 --> 00:50:28.630
of answer, which is we want a
lot of people to know of us.

00:50:28.630 --> 00:50:31.730
If God's not watching, we
want as many Twitter followers

00:50:31.730 --> 00:50:33.490
as possible.

00:50:33.490 --> 00:50:35.030
We broadcast everything.

00:50:35.030 --> 00:50:36.405
If you're in a
restaurant, people

00:50:36.405 --> 00:50:39.450
are taking pictures of their
food to put on Facebook.

00:50:39.450 --> 00:50:44.300
That sense of giving our
life a "moreness" using

00:50:44.300 --> 00:50:51.080
our social media, now that
Jehovah's no longer watching.

00:50:51.080 --> 00:50:57.240
It's very similar to what
the ancient Greek society,

00:50:57.240 --> 00:51:00.100
especially Athens, was about.

00:51:00.100 --> 00:51:06.850
And it was against that Socrates
was arguing in the Agora.

00:51:06.850 --> 00:51:08.570
That's what he was saying.

00:51:08.570 --> 00:51:12.810
When he says the unexamined
life is not worth living, which

00:51:12.810 --> 00:51:14.770
Plato has him saying
in the "Apology," which

00:51:14.770 --> 00:51:18.180
was Plato's version
of Socrates' trial,

00:51:18.180 --> 00:51:21.010
which did not end
well for Socrates,

00:51:21.010 --> 00:51:25.300
that when he's saying
that, he is antagonizing

00:51:25.300 --> 00:51:30.010
the Athenians so that
his execution is almost

00:51:30.010 --> 00:51:34.070
a foregone conclusion because
they were so concerned

00:51:34.070 --> 00:51:38.440
with feeling that they
mattered and believing

00:51:38.440 --> 00:51:42.010
that their high achievements--
and for those who couldn't

00:51:42.010 --> 00:51:44.700
achieve, just being
an Athenian, being

00:51:44.700 --> 00:51:48.360
a member of that exceptional
society-- if there

00:51:48.360 --> 00:51:50.400
was Athenian
exceptionalism, just as

00:51:50.400 --> 00:51:52.490
American
exceptionalism-- to just

00:51:52.490 --> 00:51:55.830
be a member of that society
would do it for you.

00:51:55.830 --> 00:51:56.730
You mattered.

00:51:56.730 --> 00:52:00.080
But they had this
notion of kleos,

00:52:00.080 --> 00:52:03.630
which meant to claim
and to do something, be

00:52:03.630 --> 00:52:08.100
an Olympic victor,
be a great warrior,

00:52:08.100 --> 00:52:14.090
be smart, be a good philosopher,
be a sophist, be very rich,

00:52:14.090 --> 00:52:15.020
be beautiful.

00:52:15.020 --> 00:52:17.590
They worshipped beauty
because anything

00:52:17.590 --> 00:52:21.160
that would blow your life
up so that many people would

00:52:21.160 --> 00:52:28.546
be paying attention satisfied
their notion of mattering.

00:52:28.546 --> 00:52:29.920
Because you
certainly didn't look

00:52:29.920 --> 00:52:33.110
to the Greek gods for your
affirmation of existence.

00:52:33.110 --> 00:52:35.550
The last thing you
wanted was the attention

00:52:35.550 --> 00:52:36.420
of the Greek gods.

00:52:36.420 --> 00:52:39.290
Something terrible always
happened if they paid attention

00:52:39.290 --> 00:52:43.610
to you, at the very
least a rate or worse.

00:52:43.610 --> 00:52:45.630
And so you didn't look there.

00:52:45.630 --> 00:52:47.210
You looked to your
fellow citizens

00:52:47.210 --> 00:52:48.710
and you tried to
do something big.

00:52:48.710 --> 00:52:51.550
This obviously
promoted a society

00:52:51.550 --> 00:52:55.490
of extraordinary, explosive
ambition and achievement, also

00:52:55.490 --> 00:52:57.360
havoc.

00:52:57.360 --> 00:53:05.470
But Plato, and Socrates before
him, thought that it's shallow.

00:53:05.470 --> 00:53:06.880
That's not what's
going to do it.

00:53:06.880 --> 00:53:10.780
So Plato is struck
by similarities

00:53:10.780 --> 00:53:13.940
and the way we're falling
back on social media

00:53:13.940 --> 00:53:19.000
to fill the vacuum that
monotheism has left,

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:22.900
to create a society that's very
much like the one that forced

00:53:22.900 --> 00:53:25.230
philosophy in the first place.

00:53:25.230 --> 00:53:29.410
Which is why he thinks
that our society is

00:53:29.410 --> 00:53:37.070
a ripe for again recognizing
the value of philosophy.

00:53:37.070 --> 00:53:38.980
That's what he thinks.

00:53:38.980 --> 00:53:41.732
I sort of think so too.

